(3, 'Prostate Cancer Specialist Doctor in Delhi\r\n', 'Prostate Cancer Specialist Doctor in Delhi', 'A man\'s prostate cancer, a small walnut-sized gland that produces semen.A man\'s prostate produces semen that nourishes and transports sperm.Symptoms include difficulty....\r\n\r\n', '<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">A man&apos;s prostate cancer is a small walnut-sized gland that produces semen. A man&apos;s prostate produces semen that nourishes and transports sperm. Symptoms include difficulty urinating, but sometimes there are no symptoms. Some types of prostate cancer grow slowly. In some of these cases, follow-up is recommended. Other types are aggressive and require radiation therapy, surgery, hormone therapy, chemotherapy, or other treatments.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Cancer is the #2 killer of men, accounting for 30% of all deaths in this demographic. Prostate cancer is the second-most common type of all cancers in men, after skin cancer, and the 3rd most common cause of cancer death in males. Ninety percent of cases occur after age 50 and 80% present as a localized disease (confined within the prostate).</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Prostate cancer is the second-leading cause of cancer death among men. It is diagnosed in more than 2 million people each year, and its incidence rates are higher in African American and other minority populations. Remaining silent about prostate cancer may be the biggest threat to defeating this type of cancer, so it&apos;s important to share a little bit of information to help others understand what this disease can do.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Zinc is involved in direct and indirect pathways of cell growth. In addition, zinc controls enzymatic activity and the expression of genes that regulate apoptosis and DNA synthesis. A high level of zinc may make tumors grow at a faster rate. The prostate gland produces about 20% of our body&apos;s zinc. A healthy prostate also produces testosterone, which is essential for maintaining a normal libido, erectile function, mental alertness, and muscle mass. According to the Doctor.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Read more about Immune system modulators in&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/blogs/immune-system-modulator-in-prostate-cancer/\" style=\"color: transparent;font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(41, 128, 185);\"><strong>prostate cancer</strong></span></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67); font-size: 18px;\"><strong>Symptoms of Prostate Cancer:-</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Early-stage prostate cancer may not cause any signs or symptoms. Symptoms commonly noted during the advanced stage include:</span></span></span></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: disc;list-style-position: inside;text-align: start;color: rgb(68, 68, 68);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 15px;font-family: Roboto, sans-serif;\">\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; line-height: 1.5; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Trouble urinating</span></li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; line-height: 1.5; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Frequent urination</span></li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; line-height: 1.5; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Decreased force of urination</span></li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; line-height: 1.5; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Difficulty starting or stopping the urine stream</span></li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; line-height: 1.5; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Blood in semen</span></li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; line-height: 1.5; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Pain or discomfort in the pelvic area</span></li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; line-height: 1.5; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Bone pain</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">A regular check-up every once in a while is a must, and as soon as you find any of the related symptoms, consult a </span><strong><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/about-dr-sajjan-rajpurohit/\" style=\"color: transparent;font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(41, 128, 185);\">cancer specialist in Delhi, India Dr. Sajjan Rajpurohit.&nbsp;</span></a></strong></span></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><br>&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67); font-size: 18px;\"><strong>Trouble Urinating</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Well, the truth is that these two topics are actually closely related. When it comes to peeing, drinking plenty of water and going to the bathroom regularly are key. But if you&apos;re still having trouble urinating even after trying those methods then it may be time to go see your doctor as there could be a more serious issue (like an infection) plaguing your bladder.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67); font-size: 18px;\"><strong>Frequent urination</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Frequent urination is when your bladder feels the need to be emptied of urine more than eight times during a 24-hour period. In medical terminology, this condition is also known as polyuria.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">There are many causes of frequent urination, but one of the underlying factors is diabetes.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67); font-size: 18px;\"><strong>Decreased force of urination</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">A decrease in the force of urination can occur when the body has gone through great physical stress, such as during periods of irregular food intake and lack of sleep. The kidneys play the main role in controlling this. When you are experiencing a decrease in the force of urination, it is important to find out what is causing this change so that you can handle it accordingly and keep your health at a high level.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(35, 35, 35); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 36px; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67); font-size: 18px;\"><strong>Difficulty starting or stopping the urine stream</strong></span></span></span></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Many things can cause an issue in terms of urinating which may lead to a urinary tract infection (UTI), such as a number of health conditions, kidney stones, and even dehydration. What are some ways that both men and women can start or stop their stream of urine? Take a look at this informative blog post for more information.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">As the human body ages, it is normal to experience changes that affect our ability to urinate. The process of urination may become much more difficult or even impossible in some cases.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<h1 style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(35, 35, 35); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 36px; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67); font-size: 18px;\"><strong>Blood in semen</strong></span></span></span></h1>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">The presence of blood in your semen is called hematospermia (also called hemospermia). Hematospermia can be a common concern for men who have it. However, it is unlikely to be a sign of a serious health condition.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(67, 67, 67);\">Pain or discomfort in the pelvic area</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(80, 80, 80);\">Pelvic pain is a symptom of infection. And it can cause pain in some internal organs, such as the pelvic bones or the abdomen, or the colon.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><strong>Bone pain</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">If you&rsquo;ve been experiencing different types of chronic or sudden bone pain in the last six months, you might have prostate cancer. A common symptom of prostate cancer, this pain can be felt anywhere in the body where there are bones, so it should not be dismissed as a minor issue.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><strong>Stages of Prostate Cancer:-</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><strong>Stage 1:</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> Stage 1 of Prostate Cancer is small and grows slowly. Although they occur within the prostate, they are not able to be detected during a physical exam. There are no symptoms of prostate cancer or other health problems in this stage 1st of prostate cancer.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><strong>Stage 2:</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;In stage 2 of Prostate Cancer, the doctor can feel cancer in the prostate because they are larger than cancer in stage 1 of prostate cancer. There are two types of Prostate cancer in stages 2, 2A, and 2B. 2A cancers can be T1 tumors with high PSA or T2 or T2B with low PSA. 2B cancers can be T2C tumors or those with a high PSA can be T2A or T2B.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><strong>Stage 3:&nbsp;</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Stage 3 of Prostate&nbsp;cancer has grown very rapidly outside the prostate. They may have reached the seminal vesicles and not the rectum or bladder. Stage 3 of Prostate Cancer is mostly reversible after treatment.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><strong>Stage 4:</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;Stage 4 of Prostate cancer&nbsp;is a metastasis stage. It is likely to spread to nearby organs such as the rectum, bladder, or nearby lymph nodes. Distant organs such as bones may also be affected. Mostly, this stage is not curable.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><strong>Treatments for Prostate Cancer:-</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\"><strong>Surgery &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>If prostate cancer has not spread outside the prostate gland, the surgeon may perform a radical prostatectomy to remove the entire prostate gland, surrounding tissue, and nearby lymph nodes (to prevent spread outside the prostate gland). This may involve using a laparoscopic or robotic approach or open surgery.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\">Read more about</span></span></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/robotic-surgery\" style=\"color: transparent;font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(94, 94, 94);\">&nbsp;</span><span style=\"color: rgb(41, 128, 185);\"><strong>Robotic surgery</strong></span></a></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\"><strong>Hormone therapy &ndash;</strong>&nbsp;The hormones that help cancer cells grow are blocked so that they cannot reach the cancer cells. Prostate cancer cells depend on the hormone testosterone to grow and divide. Methods include the use of drugs that reduce the production of testosterone, drugs that block the supply of testosterone, and surgical removal of the testicles to completely stop the production of testosterone. This method is used to reduce the size of cancer and is also used before radiation therapy to treat advanced cases of prostate cancer.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\">Read more about&nbsp;<strong>Hormone therapy</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\"><strong>Immunotherapy&ndash;&nbsp;</strong>In this method, the body&apos;s immune system is used to attack cancer cells. This may include- a) helping immune cells to detect and attack cancer cells; b) Genetically engineering immune cells outside the body in laboratories, and then injecting them back into the body, which can then find and kill prostate cancer cells.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\">Read more about</span></span></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/immunotherapy\" style=\"color: transparent;font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(41, 128, 185);\"><strong>&nbsp;Immunotherapy</strong></span></a></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\"><strong>Chemotherapy &ndash;&nbsp;</strong>drugs are given by intravenous injection or orally to kill cancer cells and reduce the size of the tumor. It is used to treat high-grade and fast-spreading prostate cancer that has already spread to other parts of the body.</span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(66, 62, 62);\">Read more about&nbsp;</span></span></span><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/chemotherapy\" style=\"color: transparent;font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(41, 128, 185); font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><strong>Chemotherapy</strong></span></span></span></a></p>', 'type2.jpeg', 'prostate-cancer-specialist'),
(4, 'Mouth and Oral Cancer Specialist Doctor in Delhi', 'Mouth and Oral Cancer Specialist Doctor in Delhi', 'Mouth cancer can Present anywhere in the mouth, including the inside of the lips, cheeks and gums. These are the Symptoms of mouth cancer:-Mouth enlargement....', '<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family: Arial;\"><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><strong>Mouth cancer</strong></span></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">&nbsp;is a type of cancer of the throat and head and is often treated as such. Mouth cancer mostly occurs after the age of 40, and men are more prone to it than women. A total of 77,003 new cases of mouth cancer have been registered in India this year and 52,067 people have died. Oral cancer is detected when it has spread to the lymph nodes in your neck and if oral cancer is detected early, the risk of life is low.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Types of Mouth Cancer (Oral Cancer)-</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: disc;list-style-position: inside;text-align: start;color: rgb(68, 68, 68);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 15px;font-family: Roboto, sans-serif;\">\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Lip Cancer</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Tongue Cancer</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Inner Cheek Cancer</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Gum Cancer</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Cancer of the lower part of the mouth</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">You should see your dentist as soon as you see symptoms of oral cancer. According to the dentist, at least twice a year, get your mouth examined by your doctor. Let us know about its symptoms, dangers, its stages. And you can meet Mouth Cancer Specialist </span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><strong><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/about-dr-sajjan-rajpurohit/\" style=\"color:font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\">Dr. Sajjan Rajpurohit</a></strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Symptoms of Mouth Cancer (Oral Cancer):-&nbsp;</strong></span></span><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">In the early stages of mouth cancer, it is not detected and there are no symptoms, but people who smoke or drink alcohol on a daily basis should have their mouth checked from time to time by their dentist.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>The Main Symptoms of mouth cancer (oral cancer) are as follows-</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: disc;list-style-position: inside;text-align: start;color: rgb(68, 68, 68);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);font-size: 15px;font-family: Roboto, sans-serif;\">\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Non-healing blister on the lips or mouth</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mouth enlargement</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Bleeding from the mouth</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Loose tooth</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mouth pain or difficulty swallowing</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Sudden lump in the neck</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Earache</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Sudden weight loss</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Numbness of the lips, face, neck, or chin</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Red and white patches on the mouth or lips</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Throat pain</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Dry mouth</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Jaw pain or stiffness</li>\r\n    <li style=\"list-style-type: disc; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Tongue pain</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Although having these symptoms doesn&apos;t mean you have mouth cancer, you should definitely see your dentist and continue to check on them from time to time after your visit. Some of these symptoms, such as a sore throat or earache, can also indicate some other illness. However, if you notice any of these symptoms, especially if they do not go away even with the first treatment or if there is more than one symptom at a time, do not ignore them and do not ignore them as soon as possible. See your dentist or doctor as soon as possible and get the proper treatment.</span></span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(35, 35, 35); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 30px; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Cause of Mouth cancer (Oral Cancer)</strong></span></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Smoking:&nbsp;</strong>Smoking is the most common cause of mouth cancer, and people who smoke cigarettes, cigars, or pipes have the highest risk of mouth cancer.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Consumption of tobacco:</strong> If you say tobacco in any form, then it can also become a major cause of oral cancer.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Drinking alcohol in excess.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Mouth cancer stages</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(35, 35, 35); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 30px; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>The stages of oral cancer increase as follows-</strong></span></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Stage 1:&nbsp;</strong>In this stage, the tumor is less than 1 inch in size and has not reached nearby lymph nodes.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Stage 2:</strong> The tumor grows to 1 to 2 inches and has not reached nearby lymph nodes.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Stage 3:</strong> In this stage, the tumor grows to about 2 inches but does not spread either; it does not grow more than 1 inch but has spread to nearby lymph nodes.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Stage 4:</strong> Cancer in this stage has spread to the mouth and cancer affects the tissues around the mouth, lips, and possibly nearby lymph nodes; Or it spreads to the rest of the body.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The stages of cancer tell how it can be treated as well as how likely it is to be cured.</span></span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(35, 35, 35); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 30px; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Treatment of Mouth Cancer:-</strong></span></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Some common treatments for mouth cancer are as follows:</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Surgery:</strong> In this procedure, an operation has to be done to remove the tumor from the entire mouth. A small incision is made in the neck or jaw so that the place where the tumor is located can be easily removed. After the tumor is surgically removed, that part of the mouth is reconstructed. In these cases, surgeons may perform pedicle or free flap reconstruction.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Read more about </span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><strong><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/robotic-surgery\" style=\"color:font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\">Robotic Surgery</a></strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Radiation Therapy:</strong> Radiation therapy involves the use of radiation technology to treat the area of the mouth where cancer has spread and healthy tissue is spread over that place. External beam radiation therapy (EBRT) and brachytherapy are the two most common radiation therapies used to treat oral cancer.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Read more about <strong><a href=\"http://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/radiation-therapy\" style=\"color: transparent;font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\">R</a></strong></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"http://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/radiation-therapy\" style=\"font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\"><strong>Radiation therapy</strong></a></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Chemotherapy:</strong> Chemotherapy often combined with radiation therapy is used to destroy cancer cells throughout the body using anticancer drugs to remove cancer. Cancer cells are destroyed at different stages by mixing different chemotherapy drugs.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Read more about </span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><strong><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/chemotherapy\" style=\"font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\">Chemotherapy</a></strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Targeted drug therapy:</strong> Targeted drug therapy directly strikes the cancerous cells to eliminate them from their roots and stops the cancer cells from growing. This therapy can be used in combination with both chemotherapy and/or radiation therapy to treat mouth cancer.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Read more about<a href=\"https://canceronco.com/treatments/targeted-therapy\" style=\"color: transparent;font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\">&nbsp;</a></span><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://canceronco.com/treatments-of-cancer/targeted-therapy\" style=\"font-family: Poppins, sans-serif;\"><strong>Targeted therapy</strong></a></span></span></p>\r\n<h2 style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(35, 35, 35); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 30px; font-family: Poppins, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 18px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><strong>Some important facts about Mouth Cancer:-</strong></span></span></h2>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">About 80% of Mouth Cancer cases are due to tobacco use alone.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The average age of getting mouth cancer is 50 years.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Mouth cancer rates in men are much higher than in women and these rates increase with age.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">If the symptoms of mouth cancer are recognized and treated at the very beginning, then your chances of survival increase by 82%.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Similarly, if it is identified and treated in the advanced stage, then the survival rate is up to 27%.</span></span></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: start; color: rgb(102, 102, 102); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255); font-size: 15px; font-family: Roboto, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">As soon as the symptoms of mouth cancer are seen, the dentist should be shown immediately and it should be treated properly without delay. It is often seen that Indian people do not take special care of oral health, due to which they have to face a lot of oral diseases. To avoid all kinds of oral problems, visit the dentist regularly and take special care of your oral and oral health.</span></span></p>', 'type3.jpeg', 'mouth-and-oral-cancer');
